Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: This section describes the debug menu options available in the Godot editor.

Debug menu options
There are a few common debug options you can toggle on or off when running your game in the editor, which can help you in debugging your game.

You can find these options in the Debug editor menu.

Here are the descriptions of the options:
---CHUNK---
Document: Overview of Debugging Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains the "Deploy with Remote Debug" option for debugging projects on remote devices.
Deploy with Remote Debug
When this option is enabled, using one-click deploy will make the executable attempt to connect to this computer's IP so the running project can be debugged. This option is intended to be used for remote debugging (typically with a mobile device). You don't need to enable it to use the GDScript debugger locally.
---CHUNK---
Document: overview_of_debugging_tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: This section describes the "Small Deploy with Network Filesystem" option for faster testing of large games on remote devices.
When Small Deploy with Network Filesystem is on, instead of exporting the full game, deploying the game builds a minimal executable. The editor then provides files from the project over the network. This option speeds up testing for games with a large footprint on remote devices. Also, on Android, the game is deployed using the USB cable to speed up deployment.
---CHUNK---
Document: Overview of Debugging Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: This section describes how to enable the visibility of collision shapes and raycast nodes in the running project for debugging purposes.
Visible Collision Shapes
When this option is enabled, collision shapes and raycast nodes (for 2D and 3D) will be visible in the running project.
---CHUNK---
