Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains how to customize run instances for debugging multiplayer games.
Customize Run Instances...
This opens a dialog allowing you to tell Godot to run multiple instances of the game at once, and to specify the command line arguments for each instance. This is especially useful when building and debugging multiplayer games.
---CHUNK---
Document: Overview of Debugging Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains the "Enable Multiple Instances" debugging option in Godot.
Enable Multiple Instances
When this option is enabled, the editor will run multiple instances of the project at once when you Run Project.
Below this checkbox is a selector to pick how many instances to run.
Checking the box and setting this to only 1 is the same as not checking this box at all.
---CHUNK---
Document: Overview of Debugging Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains how to configure and access command-line arguments passed to the project when running it.

Main Run Args
These are the arguments that will be passed to every instance of the project when you Run Project, unless you select "Enabled" under "Override Main Run Args" for a specific instance. Note that these arguments are space-separated. Tip: These arguments can be accessed in your script by using get_cmdline_args. Warning: Even if you uncheck "Enable Multiple Instances" these arguments will be passed when you Run Project.
---CHUNK---
Document: overview_of_debugging_tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains the concept of main feature tags in Godot's debugging tools.
These are the feature tags that will be passed to every instance of the project when you Run Project, unless you select "Enabled" under "Override Main Tags" for a specific instance.
---CHUNK---
Document: Overview of Debugging Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains the "Override Main Run Args" setting in Godot's project settings.
Override Main Run Args
When this is enabled, the arguments in the "Main Run Args" field will not be passed to this specific instance of the project when you Run Project.
---CHUNK---
Document: Overview of Debugging Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains how launch arguments are passed to a Godot project instance.
Launch Arguments
These are the arguments that will be passed to this specific instance of the project when you Run Project. They will be combined with the "Main Run Args" unless you select "Enabled" under "Override Main Run Args".
---CHUNK---
Document: Overview of Debugging Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains the functionality of the "Override Main Tags" option in project settings.
Override Main Tags: When this is enabled, the tags in the "Main Feature Tags" field will not be passed to this specific instance of the project when you Run Project.
---CHUNK---
Document: overview_of_debugging_tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: Explains how to use feature tags and command-line arguments for project debugging in Godot.
Feature Tags
These are the feature tags that will be passed to this specific instance of the project when you Run Project. They will be combined with the "Main Feature Tags" unless you select "Enabled" under "Override Main Tags".
Warning: If you want to pass "User" arguments, that can be accessed with get_cmdline_user_args then you must prefix them with two dashes and a space like -- one two three. Be aware that these dashes will apply to arguments added later in the "Launch Arguments" on a per instance basis, which can cause some confusion when combining the `Main Run Args` and `Launch Arguments`. If you place `-- one two three` in the "Main Run Args" and `-- four five six` in the "Launch Arguments" then the final command line arguments will be `one two three -- four five six`. This is because the `--` is repeated in the "Launch Arguments".
---CHUNK---
Document: Overview of Debugging Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/debug/overview_of_debugging_tools.rst
Summary: This section describes the debugging tools available in the Godot script editor, including breakpoints, stepping controls, and external debugger integration.
The script editor provides several debug tools, including breakpoint management and specific options. Breakpoint functionality is also accessible via the **Debugger** tab.

Tip: Breakpoints can be set by clicking in the script editor's gutter next to the line numbers. A transparent red dot appears on hover, becoming opaque when a breakpoint is set. Clicking the red dot again removes it. These breakpoints are saved and persist even if the script is not saved before exiting the editor. Alternatively, the `breakpoint` keyword in GDScript creates a breakpoint stored within the script file itself, making it persistent across different machines when using version control.

The **Break** button simulates a breakpoint, pausing script execution. **Continue** resumes execution after a pause. **Step Over** advances to the next line of code. **Step Into** attempts to enter a function call on the current line; if not possible, it behaves like **Step Over**.

The **Debug with External Editor** option allows debugging using an external editor. A shortcut for this feature can be configured in **Editor Settings > Shortcuts > Debugger**.

When the debugger pauses execution at a breakpoint, a green triangle arrow appears in the script editor's gutter, indicating the current line of execution.
---CHUNK---
